Abstract = {Since early 2018 the ``Natural Hazards{''} Section of Geosciences
   journal has aimed to publish pure, experimental, or applied research
   that is focused on advancing methodologies, technologies, expertise, and
   capabilities to detect, characterize, monitor, and model natural hazards
   and assess their associated risks. This stream of geoscientific research
   has reached a high degree of specialization and represents a
   multi-disciplinary research realm. To inaugurate this section, the
   Special Issue ``Key Topics and Future Perspectives in Natural Hazards
   Research{''} was launched. After a year and half since the call for
   papers was initially opened, the special issue is now completed with the
   editorial introducing the collection of 10 selected papers covering the
   following hot topics of natural hazards research: (i) trends in
   publications and research directions at international level; (ii) the
   role of Big Data in natural disaster management; (iii) assessment of
   seismic risk through the understanding and quantification of its three
   components (i.e., hazard, vulnerability and exposure/impact); (iv)
   climatic/hydro-meteorological hazards (i.e., drought, hurricanes); and
   (v) scientific analysis of past incidents and disaster forensics (i.e.,
   the Oroville Dam 2017 spillway incident). The present editorial provides
   a summary of each paper of the collection within the current context of
   scientific research on natural hazards, pointing out the salient results
   and key messages.},
